        introduction: "The Dinan to Rennes journey links one of Brittany's finest medieval walled cities to the regional capital, a 55 km drive through the heart of the Breton countryside. Dinan is a unique heritage jewel, a fortified city perched on a rocky promontory overlooking the Rance valley from three kilometres of granite ramparts — the best preserved in all of Brittany. The old town is a delight for medieval architecture enthusiasts: cobbled lanes wind between 14th and 15th-century half-timbered houses with carved and colourful facades, Renaissance stone mansions, chapels and convents testifying to the past prosperity of this merchant city. The Rue du Jerzual, the iconic street that plunges steeply from the ramparts to the Rance port, is one of Brittany's most photographed streets with its overhanging houses and artisan workshops — glass blowers, weavers and wood carvers. Dinan Castle, a 14th-century keep built by Duke Jean IV of Brittany, now houses a local history museum and offers panoramic views from its ramparts. The taxi is used by travellers connecting to the TGV at Rennes, professionals working in the Rennes metropolis, university students, and tourists wishing to combine a visit to Dinan with exploring the Breton capital.",
        itineraire: "From Dinan, your driver takes the D766 towards Rennes, a well-maintained departmental road crossing the inland Breton countryside. You leave Dinan southward, first passing the ramparts and station quarter, then the road enters the Cotes-d'Armor bocage — a landscape of hedgerows, green meadows with dairy cattle, and typical granite-and-slate Breton farmhouses. You pass through Caulnes, a small rural commune in the heart of Dinan country, then approach Becherel, the 'book town', a charming hilltop village known for its second-hand bookshops set in granite houses — on the first Sunday of each month, a book market draws bibliophiles from across Brittany. After Becherel, the road descends gradually into the Rennes basin via Romille and Pace. Arrival in Rennes is from the north-west, providing quick access to the TGV station, historic centre and business districts. The journey takes 40 minutes normally and can reach 55 minutes during Rennes rush hours.",
